      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Shortage Of Minority Teachers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Warren Harding High principal Edward C Goldstone opposes Patricia Boyle's statement in July 2 letter in response to June 11 article that black teachers feel more comfortable in urban classrooms and white teachers in suburban settings (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Patricia Boyle's July 2 letter in reference to the article on the shortage of minority teachers in Connecticut classrooms (''White Faces at the Blackboard,'' June 11) merits a response. Her statement that ''black teachers feel more comfortable in urban classrooms as do white teachers in suburban settings'' reflects the segregationist mentality that serves to confirm the need for minority teachers in all classroom settings.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Patricia Boyle's July 2 letter in reference to the article on the shortage of minority teachers in Connecticut classrooms (''White Faces at the Blackboard,'' June 11) merits a response. Her statement that ''black teachers feel more comfortable in urban classrooms as do white teachers in suburban settings'' reflects the segregationist mentality that serves to confirm the need for minority teachers in all classroom settings.</p>
        <p>As the principal of an urban school I can state without hesitation that the minority teachers on our staff would be both comfortable and effective in suburban as well urban classrooms. I agree that bonuses to minority applicants are not the answer, but her scenario of continued segregation will only widen the gap between rich and poor, white and minority.</p>
        <p>EDWARD C. GOLDSTONE  Hamden</p>
        <p>Mr. Goldstone is the principal of Bridgeport's Warren Harding High.</p>
      </block>
